le fuels seemed ok for this forum. Sometimes its difficult to draw a line. If we posted how to make a bomb then we might have the CIA breathing down our necks and yet if we posted how to build a highly potent fuel mix for model rockets we would be ok. Even if both posts described the same thing. When unsure of an item for posting I tend to veer away from censorship. Maybe we should ask uncle Sam. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=stilgar>Stilgar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/4/02 4:16:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/Bart-term.gif" align=absmiddle>  nothing</span><hr size=1> Nothing will extinguish it?  I find that hard to believe.  Where is the oxidizer?  styrofoam does not have oxygen components in it, I dont think... its just another hydrocarbon.  I made this stuff about 7-8 years ago, but I never made that much of it... I filled a jam jar.  I didnt try to light the whole thing at once... I spread it out and made words on the driveway and stuff.  I coudnt say wether its impossible to extinguish becaue I didn't try, but heres my take on this:<br><br>The styrofoam disolves and jellies in the gasoline, providing a stabilizing jelling agent.  The gasoline is what is providing the continued combustion.  the styrofoam is along for the ride.  Since there is no oxidizer(other than the atmosphere) you should be able to put it out by simply using a co2 or foam-based extinguisher. <br><br>Further thoughts:  The styrofoam gel may retain sufficient heat to reignite the flame if the oxygen supply is returned after being withdrawn, so you may have to cool the substance as well to extinguish it.  Water is not good in this application because gasoline is less dense than water (although napalm might be more dense... I'd have to experiment) and would just float on top and continue to burn.  Hrm.  This warrants further thought.<br><br>Stilgar out. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 1763<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/4/02 4:49:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  Interesting</span><hr size=1> How long did it burn? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=stilgar>Stilgar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 5<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/6/02 5:31:06 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=5.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/devil.gif" align=absmiddle>  How long</span><hr size=1> not long... little tablespoon sized chunks (I spread it around pretty well) were gone in less than a minute.  They left some oily gunk on the pavement. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspace